{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505145"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2410"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2410"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.09,0.08,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78886"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64235"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4099"},{"type":"tags","id":"4662"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1804"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of vaginal discharge and itch. The discharge is foul-smelling and frothy. She has no dyspareunia or abnormal bleeding. She has a medical history of depression and takes Microgynon 30 (ethinylestradiol and levonorgestrel) and sertraline. She is sexually active with multiple male partners and uses condoms inconsistently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Speculum examination reveals a frothy yellow-green vaginal discharge with punctate haemorrhages on the cervix. The pH of the discharge is 5.5.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trichomonas vaginalis","Neisseria gonorrhoeae","Chlamydia trachomatis","Gardnerella vaginalis","Candida albicans"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is highly suggestive of trichomoniasis. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETrichomonas vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is a sexually transmitted protozoan that characteristically causes a frothy yellow-green discharge with an elevated vaginal pH (\u0026gt;4.5). The strawberry cervix appearance, caused by punctate haemorrhages, is pathognomonic but only present in about 20% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a mucopurulent cervicitis with a creamy discharge. Associated symptoms often include dysuria, intermenstrual bleeding, and deep dyspareunia, none of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E infection is often asymptomatic (in up to 90% of cases) or may present with post-coital bleeding and mucopurulent discharge. It would not cause the characteristic frothy discharge seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGardnerella vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with bacterial vaginosis, which presents with a thin, grey, homogeneous discharge with a fishy odour. Microscopy typically reveals clue cells, and the discharge lacks the frothy appearance seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003Ecauses vulvovaginal candidiasis, characterised by thick, white, cottage cheese-like discharge with intense vulval itch. The discharge is typically odourless and the vaginal pH remains normal (3.8-4.5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment for trichomoniasis involves metronidazole (either single 2g dose or 400mg twice daily for 5-7 days) for both the patient and all sexual partners. Safe sex counselling and STI screening are essential components of management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trichomonas vaginalis infection classically presents with frothy yellow-green discharge and strawberry cervix appearance.","Multiple sexual partners increases the risk of sexually transmitted infections including trichomoniasis.","Treatment of trichomoniasis requires both patient and partner therapy to prevent reinfection."],"references":["Trichominiasis. The Australian STI guidelines [online]. [Accessed 2021 Feb 21]. Available at: http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/trichomoniasis","Sherrard J. How to diagnose and manage Trichomonas vaginalis. The Pharmaceutical Journal. 2017;299:7906. Available at: https://pharmaceutical-journal.com/article/ld/how-to-diagnose-and-manage-trichomonas-vaginalis","Van Der Pol B, Williams JA, Orr DP, et al. Prevalence, incidence, natural history, and response to treatment of Trichomonas vaginalis infection among adolescent women. J Infect Dis 2005;192:2039. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16288365/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64235"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2410"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64235"},"attributes":{"creat